<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,266,732]" pageId="14" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,266,292]" pageId="14" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Length of male 
<quantity box="[470,563,266,292]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="2.9">2.9 mm</quantity>
, female 
<quantity box="[660,752,266,292]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.1" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" unit="mm" value="3.1">3.1 mm</quantity>
. Closely resembling 
<emphasis box="[996,1202,266,291]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich &amp; Dmitriev" authorityYear="2007" box="[996,1198,266,291]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neozygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argentiniensis">N. argentiniensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but differing as follows: male pygofer (
<figureCitation box="[406,502,306,332]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="14.[151,255,1563,1587]" captionTargetBox="[278,1261,789,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-314@14.[275,1312,789,1539]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 4. New South American spp. of Neozygina, male pygofer (A, D, G, N), aedeagus in lateral (B, E, H, J, L, O) and posterior (C, F, I, K, M, P) views. A–C, N. abancayensis; D–F, N. argentiniensis; G–I, N. asymmetrica; J–K, N. expanda; L–M, N. forcipata; N–P, N. retrorsa." pageId="14" pageNumber="41">Fig. 4N</figureCitation>
) with ventral spine more elongate, strongly curved dorsad and only slightly mesad; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[366,500,346,372]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="14.[151,255,1563,1587]" captionTargetBox="[278,1261,789,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-314@14.[275,1312,789,1539]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 4. New South American spp. of Neozygina, male pygofer (A, D, G, N), aedeagus in lateral (B, E, H, J, L, O) and posterior (C, F, I, K, M, P) views. A–C, N. abancayensis; D–F, N. argentiniensis; G–I, N. asymmetrica; J–K, N. expanda; L–M, N. forcipata; N–P, N. retrorsa." pageId="14" pageNumber="41">Figs. 4O, P</figureCitation>
) without basal processes, shaft very narrowly U-shaped in lateral view, apex in posterior view with pair of short forcipate distal processes and pair of retrorse lateral preapical spines, sinuate in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
